'''''A History of the Mind: Evolution and the Birth of Consciousness''''' is a 1992 book about the [[mind–body problem]] by the psychologist [[Nicholas Humphrey]]. The book received positive reviews, but Humphrey's hypothesis about consciousness has been criticized as speculative.

==Summary==
Humphrey describes his book as "a partial history of a part of what constitutes the human mind: an evolutionary history of how sensory consciousness has come into the world and what it is doing there." He discusses the views of the poet [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]] and the philosophers [[Colin McGinn]] and [[Daniel Dennett]].{{sfn|Humphrey|1992|pages=xiii, xv, 5, 41, 170}}

==Publication history==
''A History of the Mind'' was first published by [[Chatto & Windus]] in 1992.{{sfn|Humphrey|1992|page=iv}}

==Reception==
===Mainstream media===
''A History of the Mind'' received a positive review from Francisca Goldsmith in ''[[Library Journal]]'' and a negative review from John C. Marshall in ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]''.{{sfn|Goldsmith|1992|page=70}}{{sfn|Marshall|1992|page=8}} The book was also reviewed by M. Kohn in ''[[New Statesman|New Statesman and Society]]'',{{sfn|Kohn|1992|page=39}} and by ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'',{{sfn|''Publishers Weekly''|1992|page=56}} ''[[New Scientist]]'',{{sfn|''New Scientist''|1992|page=45}} and ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]''.{{sfn|''The New York Times Book Review''|1992|page=33}}

Goldsmith wrote that the book would appeal to both "interested lay readers" and scholars.{{sfn|Goldsmith|1992|page=70}} Marshall criticized Humphrey's style of writing and wrote that his "account of the evolutionary development of consciousness" was "highly speculative" and so lacking in precision and detail that it was questionable whether it could be considered a theory. He added that Humphrey's comparison of the senses of vision and hearing to those of touch, pain, smell and taste was contradicted by physiological evidence.{{sfn|Marshall|1992|page=8}}

===Scientific and academic journals===
''A History of the Mind'' received a positive review from ''[[The Lancet]]''. It described the book as an "entertaining and well-thought out work" and Humphrey's attempt to "solve the riddle of perception, sensation, and consciousness" as brave. It considered his ideas a possible basis for "a new neurophysiology", but criticized him for misinterpreting Coleridge.{{sfn|''The Lancet''|1992|page=595}}

===Evaluations in books===
[[Richard Webster (British author)|Richard Webster]], writing in ''[[Why Freud Was Wrong]]'' (1995), called ''A History of the Mind'' one of the most interesting attempts to solve the mind–body problem. He suggested that Humphrey succeeded in eliminating mind-body dualism entirely, although he noted that details of Humphrey's hypothesis remain speculative and open to criticism and that the hypothesis was rejected by McGinn.{{sfn|Webster|2005|page=484}} The paleoanthropologist [[Donald Johanson]], writing with Blake Edgar in ''From Lucy to Language'' (1996), noted that Humphrey's hypothesis about consciousness places a different emphasis on feeling and thinking than the hypothesis about consciousness put forward by Dennett in ''[[Consciousness Explained]]'' (1991).{{sfn|Johanson|Edgar|1996|page=107}}

