{{Infobox person | name = Eugenie Magnus Ingleton | image = Eugenie Magnus Ingleton 1915.jpg | imagesize = | caption = | birth_date = 1873 | birth_place = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]] | death_date = 3 August 1936 | death_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[United States]] | othername = | occupation = Screenwriter | yearsactive = }} '''Eugenie Magnus Ingleton''' (1873 - 3 August 1936) was a British [[screenwriter]], actress and war correspondent. Magnus Ingleton starting acting on the stage at the age of ten playing Little Eva in ''[[Uncle Tom’s Cabin]]''. <ref name=wfpp>{{cite web |url=https://wfpp.cdrs.columbia.edu/pioneer/ccp-eugenie-magnus-ingleton/ |title=Eugenie Magnus Ingleton |publisher=Women Film Pioneers Project |accessdate=2018-03-30 }}</ref> She worked as a war correspondent in South Africa during the [[Second Boer War]]<ref name=wfpp /><ref name="Edy2016">{{cite book|author=Carolyn M. Edy|title=The Woman War Correspondent, the U.S. Military, and the Press: 1846–1947|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Nwt7DQAAQBAJ&pg=PA138|date=13 December 2016|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1-4985-3928-9|page=138}}</ref> before moving to the United States. She worked mainly as a screenwriter but got also involved in stage design and other tasks around the set.<ref name="Cooper2010">{{cite book|author=Mark Garrett Cooper|title=Universal Women: Filmmaking and Institutional Change in Early Hollywood|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uoigTR3hPzsC&pg=PA142|date=10 March 2010|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-03522-7|pages=142–144}}</ref><ref name="Koszarski2005">{{cite book|author=Richard Koszarski|title=Fort Lee: The Film Town (1904-2004)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gvEmDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA173|date=2 March 2005|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=978-0-86196-942-5|pages=173–174}}</ref>
